915
01:24:51,913 --> 01:24:55,831
It would be awful.
Because the magic is gone.

916
01:24:56,071 --> 01:25:00,470
As it would with the tramp.

917
01:25:00,710 --> 01:25:04,388
Tell me I'm right.

918
01:25:04,468 --> 01:25:08,467
I'm in the word business,
so I have to say you're wrong.

919
01:25:08,707 --> 01:25:13,185
But I'm glad I got to meet you.

920
01:25:13,905 --> 01:25:17,623
Enjoyed the dancing?

921
01:25:17,863 --> 01:25:21,342
Yeah. And the talking.

922
01:25:27,260 --> 01:25:31,138
Take Mr. Curb to his office.

923
01:25:38,216 --> 01:25:42,214
Rollie! Get them all back.
Syd, we're in business!

924
01:25:42,454 --> 01:25:45,413
How does a blind girl mistake
a tramp for a rich man?

925
01:25:45,653 --> 01:25:48,932
When she hears a door slam
on the rich man's car.

926
01:25:49,172 --> 01:25:52,171
She thinks the tramp's the owner.

927
01:25:52,371 --> 01:25:57,209
Easy. When you know how.

928
01:26:06,166 --> 01:26:09,045
Boys!

929
01:26:18,081 --> 01:26:23,759
Boys!
I'm taking your ball to the cellar.

930
01:26:23,879 --> 01:26:28,078
I don't see any stairs.

931
01:26:38,634 --> 01:26:42,992
Mum's here. Off you go!

932
01:26:43,112 --> 01:26:46,711
Your mummy's here.

933
01:26:48,830 --> 01:26:54,628
I'll see you next weekend.
Come on, off you go!

934
01:27:17,100 --> 01:27:21,898
It can't be all that bad, Mr. Chaplin.

935
01:27:22,138 --> 01:27:24,217
Do I know you?

936
01:27:24,457 --> 01:27:26,217
And why don't I?

937
01:27:26,457 --> 01:27:28,936
I'm Paulette Levy.

938
01:27:29,176 --> 01:27:31,974
Would you like a drink?

939
01:27:32,214 --> 01:27:34,214
I already have one.

940
01:27:34,454 --> 01:27:38,052
A fur coat?

941
01:27:38,732 --> 01:27:42,291
You look hungry.

942
01:27:47,769 --> 01:27:50,328
Actress?

943
01:27:50,568 --> 01:27:54,166
If you watch B movies and don't blink.

944
01:27:54,406 --> 01:27:57,525
But don't get any ideas.
- You're taken.

945
01:27:57,765 --> 01:28:03,243
No, but I'm twenty-one.
Way too old for you.

946
01:28:04,243 --> 01:28:07,042
You're very pretty, Miss Levy.

947
01:28:07,282 --> 01:28:10,560
I didn't get here
thanks to my Shakespeare reviews.

948
01:28:10,800 --> 01:28:14,399
May I say something?
You'd be prettier as a brunette.

949
01:28:14,639 --> 01:28:19,277
You'd be devastating
if you were 6 inches taller.

950
01:28:19,517 --> 01:28:23,356
Punch? Two, please.

951
01:28:23,596 --> 01:28:26,395
At least you can do something
about your hair.

952
01:28:26,635 --> 01:28:31,433
Never! I was born this way.

953
01:28:34,072 --> 01:28:37,831
Nice to see you again, sir.

954
01:28:49,666 --> 01:28:52,305
Evening, Mr. Chaplin.

955
01:28:52,545 --> 01:28:57,104
Sorry,
I'm waiting for a natural blonde.

956
01:29:02,062 --> 01:29:03,581
You look beautiful.

957
01:29:03,821 --> 01:29:09,219
My usual table.
- Of course. Right this way.

958
01:29:20,175 --> 01:29:23,214
You'd come a long way.
- Yes. My own suit.

959
01:29:23,454 --> 01:29:27,213
No need to book a table.
I lived in luxury. But I was blind.

960
01:29:27,452 --> 01:29:28,692
Blind?

961
01:29:28,932 --> 01:29:31,931
Yes. That's fatal, for a storyteller.

962
01:29:32,171 --> 01:29:36,249
Did I tell you I sold all my stocks
the year before the Crash?

963
01:29:36,489 --> 01:29:40,248
That was clever.

964
01:29:40,648 --> 01:29:45,566
It was deeply cruel, the Depression.

965
01:29:46,046 --> 01:29:49,844
Can I have an autograph, Mr. Chaplin?

966
01:29:50,084 --> 01:29:53,763
Yes, of course.

967
01:29:58,921 --> 01:30:02,120
I wish they'd wanted my money.

968
01:30:02,360 --> 01:30:07,518
You know what?
I've always had that gift.

969
01:30:08,837 --> 01:30:14,755
After a man makes love to me,
he just goes wild from happiness.

970
01:30:14,995 --> 01:30:17,794
I am happy.

971
01:30:18,034 --> 01:30:23,432
Then I don't want to be around
when you're sad.

972
01:30:26,511 --> 01:30:30,270
Terrible things have happened
since the Crash.

973
01:30:30,510 --> 01:30:33,908
Millions of Americans
have been robbed of work.

974
01:30:34,148 --> 01:30:39,546
Machinery is replacing manpower.

975
01:30:39,906 --> 01:30:43,825
And I've said nothing.

976
01:30:46,384 --> 01:30:50,102
Shame on me.

977
01:30:50,782 --> 01:30:54,381
Shame on me.

978
01:31:16,893 --> 01:31:20,691
You're right, Charlie.
It's three seconds too short.

979
01:31:20,931 --> 01:31:26,729
Okay, we'll do a two-bar repeat
of the xylophone.

980
01:31:28,728 --> 01:31:30,288
Sorry, darling.

981
01:31:30,528 --> 01:31:34,726
I'm taking the boys out today.
Why don't you come?

982
01:31:34,966 --> 01:31:39,764
Tomorrow, darling.
Definitely tomorrow.

983
01:31:42,443 --> 01:31:44,243
Put that in straight away.

984
01:31:44,483 --> 01:31:48,601
What should we do?
- Change the key.

985
01:31:48,841 --> 01:31:52,200
Let me hear it.

986
01:31:56,238 --> 01:32:00,437
No. I'll tell you why.

987
01:32:09,074 --> 01:32:13,032
Charlie, you were supposed
to meet us at the fight.

988
01:32:13,272 --> 01:32:16,031
I'm sorry. Who was fighting?

989
01:32:16,271 --> 01:32:18,550
Mostly Mary and Doug.

990
01:32:18,790 --> 01:32:23,548
You're wonderful, Miss Goddard.

991
01:32:30,986 --> 01:32:35,264
That didn't work either, did it?

992
01:32:56,337 --> 01:32:59,615
The Fairbanks are getting a divorce.

993
01:32:59,855 --> 01:33:03,894
Mussolini has invaded Abyssinia.

994
01:33:04,134 --> 01:33:06,893
You really need a break, Charlie.

995
01:33:07,133 --> 01:33:08,892
We should take a trip.

996
01:33:09,132 --> 01:33:11,051
Good idea.

997
01:33:11,291 --> 01:33:13,610
What's a good idea?

998
01:33:13,850 --> 01:33:18,289
Around the world, I thought.

999
01:33:20,008 --> 01:33:24,006
I'm not going to make it.

1000
01:33:31,004 --> 01:33:35,802
Did you lose your other wives
this way?

1001
01:33:36,042 --> 01:33:38,561
I think so.

1002
01:33:38,801 --> 01:33:43,479
But you'd have to ask them.

1003
01:33:48,717 --> 01:33:51,237
Paulette. She was wonderful.

1004
01:33:51,476 --> 01:33:54,315
Her personality, you mean?

1005
01:33:54,555 --> 01:33:57,354
In bed?
- No. Well, that was good.

1006
01:33:57,594 --> 01:33:59,913
She didn't take me for a fortune.

1007
01:34:00,153 --> 01:34:04,512
Let me help you. Come on.

1008
01:34:06,351 --> 01:34:09,470
Okay?

1009
01:34:10,550 --> 01:34:17,227
I know you so well. I know you're
thinking of Doug, aren't you?

1010
01:34:17,467 --> 01:34:22,305
I was the only one who knew.

1011
01:34:25,664 --> 01:34:30,462
Don't say I don't look after you.

1012
01:34:35,900 --> 01:34:39,619
Mr. Chaplin. Always a pleasure.

1013
01:34:39,859 --> 01:34:41,698
How are you?

1014
01:34:41,938 --> 01:34:43,298
You look even prettier.

1015
01:34:43,538 --> 01:34:47,536
Nobody's fine and everyone needs
a drink. Champagne, scotch?

1016
01:34:47,776 --> 01:34:49,935
Scotch.

1017
01:34:50,175 --> 01:34:51,655
Is he, uh...?

1018
01:34:51,894 --> 01:34:53,574
Yes.

1019
01:34:53,814 --> 01:34:57,013
Seriously?

1020
01:34:57,253 --> 01:35:01,971
His heart.
- Shit.

1021
01:35:07,329 --> 01:35:09,488
Hey. Don't laugh.

1022
01:35:09,728 --> 01:35:12,407
I'm testing for Scarlett.

1023
01:35:12,647 --> 01:35:13,647
Why should I laugh?

1024
01:35:13,886 --> 01:35:17,525
Because it's a joke.
Everyone's testing for Scarlett.

1025
01:35:17,765 --> 01:35:22,084
I hear Katie Hepburn has it locked
away. So they say.

1026
01:35:22,323 --> 01:35:24,523
I haven't worked
since "Modern Times".

1027
01:35:24,763 --> 01:35:26,482
Neither have I.

1028
01:35:26,722 --> 01:35:30,480
No ideas. I'm desperate.

1029
01:35:30,720 --> 01:35:34,919
See you later.

1030
01:35:36,998 --> 01:35:38,558
I can manage a double.

1031
01:35:38,797 --> 01:35:40,357
Should you?

1032
01:35:40,597 --> 01:35:45,035
Are you two still married or what?
I find it very confusing.

1033
01:35:45,275 --> 01:35:50,153
When people thought we were having
an affair, we were married.

1034
01:35:50,393 --> 01:35:52,313
Now people know,
we're getting divorced.

1035
01:35:52,552 --> 01:35:56,351
You're a wizard with women,
no question about it.

1036
01:35:56,591 --> 01:35:59,790
Who's that man? Sounds German.
- Looks German.

1037
01:36:00,030 --> 01:36:04,628
Probably one of those directors.
Maybe he has a job for me.

1038
01:36:04,868 --> 01:36:09,866
Like Plato, Adolf Hitler is defining
the ideal state to be a model...

1039
01:36:10,106 --> 01:36:11,905
...for backward systems.

1040
01:36:12,145 --> 01:36:14,784
Do you know him?

1041
01:36:15,024 --> 01:36:18,063
I have that good fortune, yes.

1042
01:36:18,303 --> 01:36:20,702
And you have my word.

1043
01:36:20,942 --> 01:36:25,261
We only desire to defend our
historical frontiers. That's paramount.

1044
01:36:25,500 --> 01:36:27,100
Told you. Paramount.

1045
01:36:27,340 --> 01:36:28,699
It's not funny.

1046
01:36:28,939 --> 01:36:34,177
He merely wants to improve
the situation for the German people.

1047
01:36:34,417 --> 01:36:37,416
How can they let these fascist thugs...

1048
01:36:37,656 --> 01:36:40,975
To cut out the profit speculator.

1049
01:36:41,215 --> 01:36:42,774
The Jew.

1050
01:36:43,014 --> 01:36:48,052
Mr. Chaplin!
I am a great admirer of yours.

1051
01:36:48,292 --> 01:36:52,051
I'm sorry.
I don't shake hands with nazis.

1052
01:36:52,291 --> 01:36:55,809
What have you got against us?

1053
01:36:56,049 --> 01:36:59,568
What have you got
against everyone else?

1054
01:36:59,808 --> 01:37:03,407
You must forgive Mr. Chaplin.
He's a Jew.

1055
01:37:03,647 --> 01:37:05,766
So!

1056
01:37:06,006 --> 01:37:10,644
I'm afraid I don't have that honour.

1057
01:37:10,884 --> 01:37:13,923
Shame on you!

1058
01:37:16,442 --> 01:37:19,961
The former Miss Levy.

1059
01:37:21,160 --> 01:37:24,879
Shall we, my dear?

1060
01:37:32,516 --> 01:37:35,035
God bless you, Charlie.

1061
01:37:35,275 --> 01:37:36,635
I'll call you.

1062
01:37:36,874 --> 01:37:40,393
Yes. Please do.

1063
01:37:43,512 --> 01:37:46,591
A fine international incident
you caused!

1064
01:37:46,831 --> 01:37:48,670
Let's go out.

1065
01:37:48,910 --> 01:37:52,429
Not tonight, old darling.
I'm a bit tired.

1066
01:37:52,709 --> 01:37:57,027
It's funny, you look a lot like him.

1067
01:37:57,267 --> 01:38:01,106
Adolf, I mean.

1068
01:38:03,145 --> 01:38:05,424
With your moustache on.

1069
01:38:05,664 --> 01:38:09,942
I think he stole your act.

1070
01:38:10,382 --> 01:38:13,221
'Night, old boy.

1071
01:38:13,461 --> 01:38:16,860
'Night.

1072
01:38:17,100 --> 01:38:20,858
Sweet prince.

1073
01:38:23,697 --> 01:38:26,337
So much ended around then.

1074
01:38:26,576 --> 01:38:29,135
I'd been there 25 years.

1075
01:38:29,375 --> 01:38:32,254
Everyone else had gone over to sound.

1076
01:38:32,494 --> 01:38:37,372
I don't know
if I could resist it much longer.

1077
01:38:37,612 --> 01:38:40,331
Of course, U.A. was over for me.

1078
01:38:40,571 --> 01:38:43,650
United Artists.

1079
01:38:43,890 --> 01:38:48,289
You haven't written anything
about how that began.

1080
01:38:48,528 --> 01:38:52,327
I'll put something in.
It was a great idea, I think.

1081
01:38:52,567 --> 01:38:56,406
Creative people had their say
for the first time.

1082
01:38:56,645 --> 01:38:59,085
No milk.

1083
01:38:59,325 --> 01:39:04,523
A distributor said, "The Lunatics
have taken over the asylum".

1084
01:39:04,763 --> 01:39:09,641
That became quite a famous remark.

1085
01:39:14,599 --> 01:39:18,558
But U.A. did mean a lot to Doug.

1086
01:39:18,797 --> 01:39:22,036
When my mother died, it was sad.

1087
01:39:22,276 --> 01:39:26,315
But she was old, she'd had her run.

1088
01:39:26,555 --> 01:39:29,194
It was different with Doug.

1089
01:39:29,434 --> 01:39:33,392
Even today, I still miss him.

1090
01:39:33,632 --> 01:39:38,190
Tell me, when did you start
"The Great Dictator"?

1091
01:39:38,430 --> 01:39:40,270
'38.

1092
01:39:40,510 --> 01:39:43,708
And everyone thought you were crazy.

1093
01:39:43,948 --> 01:39:48,227
But when the war broke out,
you became a genius.

1094
01:39:48,467 --> 01:39:52,905
Not to those
who thought I was a communist.

1095
01:40:00,462 --> 01:40:05,380
Commen fr der hair-dryen!

1096
01:40:08,779 --> 01:40:14,457
Und lager beer mit pizza parliament!

1097
01:40:19,095 --> 01:40:23,494
Big smile!

1098
01:40:25,693 --> 01:40:30,131
I know you. You bastard.

1099
01:40:31,091 --> 01:40:35,250
Syd? Is that you?

1100
01:40:37,969 --> 01:40:42,887
What's wrong? You wanted to make me
a talkie. Now I'm making a talkie.

1101
01:40:43,127 --> 01:40:47,405
Yeah, but not this.

1102
01:40:49,324 --> 01:40:51,724
I know this man.

1103
01:40:51,964 --> 01:40:56,122
I'm born the same year,
four days apart.

1104
01:40:56,362 --> 01:40:59,361
He's like me, capable of anything.

1105
01:40:59,601 --> 01:41:02,400
Nobody wants to see a film...

1106
01:41:02,640 --> 01:41:05,159
...about Adolf fucking Hitler!

1107
01:41:05,399 --> 01:41:09,957
I do!

1108
01:41:10,717 --> 01:41:13,236
You're missing the point.

1109
01:41:13,476 --> 01:41:16,675
It's not about Hitler,
it's about the Tramp.

1110
01:41:16,914 --> 01:41:20,393
The little Jewish barber
taking his place.

1111
01:41:20,633 --> 01:41:23,592
What's happening in Europe
is not our problem.

1112
01:41:23,832 --> 01:41:27,031
Ninety percent of the Americans
want to stay out of the war.

1113
01:41:27,271 --> 01:41:31,589
That's nine out of ten!
It's not your business.

1114
01:41:31,829 --> 01:41:34,308
You're a comic.

1115
01:41:34,548 --> 01:41:39,346
Yes, Syd. And you're a Jew.

1116
01:41:45,424 --> 01:41:49,982
Nevertheless, I've got to give it a try.

1117
01:41:50,222 --> 01:41:55,700
Otherwise, what have I been doing
all these years?

1118
01:41:55,940 --> 01:42:00,858
I know talking
will be the end of the Tramp.

1119
01:42:01,098 --> 01:42:06,976
But at least he'll say something
I believe in.

1120
01:42:07,336 --> 01:42:12,054
Okay. We'll see how it goes.

1121
01:42:13,094 --> 01:42:18,132
"The Great Dictator"
Scene y-11-a, take one.

1122
01:42:21,371 --> 01:42:25,010
I'm sorry, but I'm not an emperor.

1123
01:42:25,250 --> 01:42:28,009
I don't want to rule or conquer anyone.

1124
01:42:28,249 --> 01:42:30,568
I'd like to help everyone, if possible.

1125
01:42:30,808 --> 01:42:33,487
Jew, gentile, black man, white.

1126
01:42:33,727 --> 01:42:37,165
We all want to help one another.
People are like that.

1127
01:42:37,405 --> 01:42:40,564
We want to live by each other's
happiness, not misery.

1128
01:42:40,804 --> 01:42:45,442
Greed has poisoned men's souls
and barricaded the world with hate.

1129
01:42:45,682 --> 01:42:48,841
It's goose-stepped us
into misery and bloodshed.

1130
01:42:49,081 --> 01:42:50,600
Do not despair.

1131
01:42:50,840 --> 01:42:53,959
The hate of men will pass,
and dictators die.

1132
01:42:54,199 --> 01:42:56,958
He's not talking about Germany...

1133
01:42:57,198 --> 01:43:01,636
He's talking about America.
Turn that damn thing down!

1134
01:43:01,876 --> 01:43:08,354
This is what we need
to make people understand.

1135
01:43:13,592 --> 01:43:17,910
Mr. Seeley,
you're looking a little pale.

1136
01:43:18,150 --> 01:43:20,909
You need a trip to California.

1137
01:43:21,149 --> 01:43:22,709
Comrades!

1138
01:43:22,949 --> 01:43:24,828
Let us fight for a new world.

1139
01:43:25,068 --> 01:43:27,547
Commie bastard!

1140
01:43:27,787 --> 01:43:32,865
Soldiers! In the name of democracy,
let us unite!

1141
01:43:34,344 --> 01:43:36,464
What brings you here?

1142
01:43:36,704 --> 01:43:40,302
My firm is getting into movies.

1143
01:43:41,342 --> 01:43:46,540
But I really don't know
much about it.

1144
01:43:47,980 --> 01:43:52,898
Congratulations on the London opening.

1145
01:43:53,338 --> 01:43:55,697
Tea is on it's way, sir.

1146
01:43:55,937 --> 01:44:00,335
Lovely afternoon, Charlie.

1147
01:44:05,813 --> 01:44:12,211
Women drop handkerchiefs.
Men must drop other things.

1148
01:44:25,086 --> 01:44:29,165
"Upper regional domes
immensely expensive. "

1149
01:44:29,404 --> 01:44:32,643
That's how you describe Joan Barry.

1150
01:44:32,883 --> 01:44:37,402
She was very well-endowed,
is that what you mean?

1151
01:44:37,641 --> 01:44:40,960
You expect people to believe
it wasn't just sex?

1152
01:44:41,200 --> 01:44:45,519
Well, I didn't have to put a girl
under contract to sleep with her.

1153
01:44:45,759 --> 01:44:47,518
I spent thousands on her.

1154
01:44:47,758 --> 01:44:49,877
I wrote a screen-play for her.

1155
01:44:50,117 --> 01:44:53,916
I don't care what the readers think.
Joan definitely had talent.

1156
01:44:54,155 --> 01:44:58,714
She was intelligent. She was pretty.
She was willing to work hard.

1157
01:44:58,954 --> 01:45:04,032
And the screen test proved
that she was very photogenic.

1158
01:45:04,272 --> 01:45:07,111
But she became erratic.

1159
01:45:07,351 --> 01:45:11,669
For some reason she began
to have some kind of breakdown.

1160
01:45:11,909 --> 01:45:17,227
She took to driving to my house,
drunk, in the middle of the night.

1161
01:45:17,467 --> 01:45:21,785
She was arrested. Made a scene.

1162
01:45:22,025 --> 01:45:26,584
I refused to have anything further
to do with her.

1163
01:45:26,824 --> 01:45:29,782
How could you have been so foolish?

1164
01:45:30,022 --> 01:45:32,621
You took up with a crazy girl...

1165
01:45:32,861 --> 01:45:35,700
A promiscuous, vengeful liar.

1166
01:45:35,940 --> 01:45:40,099
And for the first time,
you didn't propose marriage.

1167
01:45:40,339 --> 01:45:43,058
Hoover had kept tabs on you
for 20 years.

1168
01:45:43,298 --> 01:45:46,017
And he still couldn't nail you until...

1169
01:45:46,257 --> 01:45:51,774
...you played it right into his hands
by shutting Joan out.

1170
01:45:53,774 --> 01:45:55,453
You're improving.

1171
01:45:55,693 --> 01:45:58,052
Can't you find someone else
to play with?

1172
01:45:58,292 --> 01:46:02,691
Apparently not. Not anymore.

1173
01:46:02,770 --> 01:46:04,170
Who's that?

1174
01:46:04,410 --> 01:46:06,089
The debutante.

1175
01:46:06,329 --> 01:46:08,448
You're doing a favour for her agent.

1176
01:46:08,688 --> 01:46:12,407
Not another one who wants to act.
It's endless.

1177
01:46:12,647 --> 01:46:14,726
This is the last time.

1178
01:46:14,966 --> 01:46:19,484
They think it's so easy. I bet as
a child, she wanted to be a fireman.

1179
01:46:19,724 --> 01:46:23,043
In half an hour, say I have an
appointment. Someone important.

1180
01:46:23,283 --> 01:46:24,563
Leave it to me.

1181
01:46:24,802 --> 01:46:27,801
Mr. Chaplin?

1182
01:46:28,041 --> 01:46:32,200
I'm Oona O'Neill.

1183
01:46:33,399 --> 01:46:36,518
If I'm interrupting your game,
I can always come back...

1184
01:46:36,758 --> 01:46:39,197
No. No.

1185
01:46:39,437 --> 01:46:43,636
I was waiting for you.

1186
01:46:46,914 --> 01:46:50,593
I always have tea at 4:00.
How long have you been here?

1187
01:46:50,833 --> 01:46:53,432
Just this summer.

1188
01:46:53,672 --> 01:46:57,591
My agent got me
a screen test at Fox.

1189
01:46:57,830 --> 01:47:00,789
Will they give you a contract?

1190
01:47:01,029 --> 01:47:04,068
I don't know.

1191
01:47:04,308 --> 01:47:07,347
Will you tell me?

1192
01:47:07,587 --> 01:47:10,146
Yes, if you want me to.

1193
01:47:10,386 --> 01:47:11,985
Charlie!

1194
01:47:12,225 --> 01:47:16,024
Excuse me.
It's nearly time for your appointment.

1195
01:47:16,264 --> 01:47:19,383
Appointment?

1196
01:47:24,021 --> 01:47:26,300
Who's it with?

1197
01:47:26,540 --> 01:47:28,299
Uh, Fred.

1198
01:47:28,539 --> 01:47:30,339
Fred.

1199
01:47:30,579 --> 01:47:32,618
Not Astaire again.

1200
01:47:32,858 --> 01:47:34,217
That's right.

1201
01:47:34,457 --> 01:47:35,777
And Ginger?

1202
01:47:36,017 --> 01:47:37,896
Could be.

1203
01:47:38,136 --> 01:47:40,175
I'm sick of them.

1204
01:47:40,415 --> 01:47:44,573
I'm not teaching them any more.
Let them make it on their own.

1205
01:47:44,813 --> 01:47:48,372
Right.

1206
01:47:50,491 --> 01:47:55,849
Sorry. I asked him to interrupt
in case I was...

1207
01:47:56,089 --> 01:48:00,608
I mean, in case you were...

1208
01:48:03,886 --> 01:48:07,965
I've never been to England.

1209
01:48:54,748 --> 01:48:57,587
All proceeds from tonight's world
premiere...

1210
01:48:57,827 --> 01:49:02,505
...will benefit families of American
soldiers serving overseas.

1211
01:49:05,944 --> 01:49:09,343
George, I've written this for the end.

1212
01:49:09,583 --> 01:49:13,381
For the last 20 years,
I have known happiness.

1213
01:49:13,621 --> 01:49:17,780
I wish I could write more about this.
But, it involves love.

1214
01:49:18,019 --> 01:49:21,578
Perfect love is the most beautiful
of all frustrations.

1215
01:49:21,818 --> 01:49:25,977
Because it is more
than one can express.

1216
01:49:26,217 --> 01:49:29,455
Excuse me, sir.

1217
01:49:29,495 --> 01:49:31,215
Sorry for the intrusion.

1218
01:49:31,455 --> 01:49:35,253
It's all right. Come in.

1219
01:49:37,932 --> 01:49:39,892
What is it?

1220
01:49:40,131 --> 01:49:43,610
I just took a call from Miss Barry, sir.

1221
01:49:43,850 --> 01:49:49,048
She wanted me to tell you
that she's pregnant.

1222
01:50:02,003 --> 01:50:03,203
Where's Charles?

1223
01:50:03,443 --> 01:50:06,522
With Harry.

1224
01:50:06,802 --> 01:50:09,801
He may be on the stage by now.

1225
01:50:10,041 --> 01:50:13,639
Is Charles down there?

1226
01:50:20,077 --> 01:50:24,715
She'll drop the paternity suit.
Her lawyers said she'll settle.

1227
01:50:24,955 --> 01:50:28,594
No. What? Just listen.

1228
01:50:28,834 --> 01:50:33,192
She'll take $ 150,000.
That's nothing, compared to a trial.

1229
01:50:33,432 --> 01:50:38,390
She says you did it at Christmas
when she came to your house.

1230
01:50:38,630 --> 01:50:42,229
I've never made you a deal
this good, kid.

1231
01:50:42,469 --> 01:50:46,147
It was over before Christmas.
It's not my child.

1232
01:50:46,387 --> 01:50:47,427
It'll be out of the way.

1233
01:50:47,667 --> 01:50:51,745
I can't do that. I've got Oona to think of.
I must prove my innocence.

1234
01:50:51,985 --> 01:50:57,863
I'm all for proving your innocence,
but how?

1235
01:50:59,223 --> 01:51:02,222
Go back to them.

1236
01:51:02,461 --> 01:51:04,381
I beg you.

1237
01:51:04,621 --> 01:51:07,420
Get them to agree to a blood test.

1238
01:51:07,660 --> 01:51:10,659
So that night you went to his house...

1239
01:51:10,898 --> 01:51:15,617
...did you and Mr. Chaplin
have sexual relations?

1240
01:51:15,857 --> 01:51:18,296
Doesn't it look like it?

1241
01:51:18,536 --> 01:51:21,655
Never mind what it looks like.
Did you?

1242
01:51:21,894 --> 01:51:27,412
She said she did.
Why else agree to a blood test?

1243
01:51:27,692 --> 01:51:31,131
The next morning,
he just called a cab.

1244
01:51:31,371 --> 01:51:35,130
Paid me off.

1245
01:51:35,689 --> 01:51:40,728
He wanted somebody younger.
Classier.

1246
01:51:40,967 --> 01:51:44,006
Didn't he?

1247
01:52:07,078 --> 01:52:09,917
Yes, thank you.

1248
01:52:10,157 --> 01:52:12,316
It's all over.

1249
01:52:12,556 --> 01:52:17,754
The test proved it's not my baby.

1250
01:52:23,632 --> 01:52:26,751
Let's just forget all this new-fangled
rubbish about blood-tests.

1251
01:52:26,991 --> 01:52:31,189
Put it out of our minds.
His honour has ruled them...

1252
01:52:31,429 --> 01:52:33,708
...inadmissible.

1253
01:52:33,948 --> 01:52:37,427
What matters now is the financial
future of this poor child.

1254
01:52:37,667 --> 01:52:41,226
It is her future
the State is here to protect.

1255
01:52:41,465 --> 01:52:43,785
It makes me mad...

1256
01:52:44,025 --> 01:52:47,063
...how this fellow tries to put it
over us simpletons.

1257
01:52:47,303 --> 01:52:49,023
This great star...

1258
01:52:49,263 --> 01:52:50,982
...of stage and screen...

1259
01:52:51,222 --> 01:52:53,661
...who has enjoyed our hospitality
for 30 years without...

1260
01:52:53,901 --> 01:52:59,979
...applying for American citizenship.

1261
01:53:00,499 --> 01:53:03,418
But what good has his money done
Chaplin?

1262
01:53:03,657 --> 01:53:06,097
Wasting his time debauching girls.

1263
01:53:06,336 --> 01:53:08,536
What good has it done America?

1264
01:53:08,776 --> 01:53:12,814
This is the kind of stuff
that makes for communism.

1265
01:53:13,054 --> 01:53:14,893
Now my client...

1266
01:53:15,133 --> 01:53:17,612
...on the other hand...

1267
01:53:17,852 --> 01:53:19,971
...is, alas...

1268
01:53:20,211 --> 01:53:23,850
...no more moral than Chaplin.

1269
01:53:24,090 --> 01:53:28,728
Ah, yes. Yes.
They're both equally guilty.

1270
01:53:28,968 --> 01:53:32,967
Only Chaplin is old enough
to be her father.

1271
01:53:33,207 --> 01:53:34,966
Prowling around with girls.

1272
01:53:35,206 --> 01:53:41,404
Members of the jury, use your common
sense, and just look at this man.

1273
01:53:41,644 --> 01:53:46,482
This cheap, Cockney cad.

1274
01:53:47,122 --> 01:53:50,041
This...

1275
01:53:50,400 --> 01:53:53,679
...little tramp.

1276
01:53:53,919 --> 01:53:56,998
Then take a very good look at...

1277
01:53:57,238 --> 01:54:01,316
...innocent Carol Ann.

1278
01:54:01,356 --> 01:54:04,635
I defy you not to see
the resemblance.

1279
01:54:04,875 --> 01:54:09,913
Gentlemen an ladies... wives and
mothers everywhere are watching you.

1280
01:54:10,153 --> 01:54:14,712
Watching to see you stop Chaplin
in his tracks.

1281
01:54:14,951 --> 01:54:20,030
You'll sleep well the night
you give this baby a name.

1282
