1293
01:55:30,404 --> 01:55:32,683
Are you a communist, Mr. Chaplin?

1294
01:55:32,923 --> 01:55:35,482
Are you a fellow traveller?

1295
01:55:35,722 --> 01:55:38,761
Will you attend
the McCarthy hearings?

1296
01:55:39,001 --> 01:55:41,280
Gentlemen, please.

1297
01:55:41,520 --> 01:55:46,918
Mr. Chaplin has said he will go
whenever he is called.

1298
01:55:47,878 --> 01:55:49,597
Senator Joseph McCarthy

1299
01:55:49,837 --> 01:55:51,196
Even if there's one communist...

1300
01:55:51,436 --> 01:55:55,395
...in the state department...

1301
01:55:55,635 --> 01:56:00,673
...that would still be
one communist too many.

1302
01:56:00,793 --> 01:56:03,832
Mr. Lawson, are you now
or have you ever been...

1303
01:56:04,072 --> 01:56:08,190
...a member of the communist party?

1304
01:56:16,547 --> 01:56:19,746
I'm responding in the only way
in which any American...

1305
01:56:19,986 --> 01:56:22,345
...can respond to a question
which absolutely invades...

1306
01:56:22,585 --> 01:56:27,103
Then you refuse to answer, correct?

1307
01:56:27,343 --> 01:56:30,382
I have said I will offer my beliefs...

1308
01:56:30,622 --> 01:56:32,941
Stand away from the stand.

1309
01:56:33,181 --> 01:56:34,741
Stand away from the stand!

1310
01:56:34,981 --> 01:56:39,779
I am fighting for the Bill of Rights!

1311
01:56:46,936 --> 01:56:50,135
I'd love to get away for a while.

1312
01:56:50,375 --> 01:56:55,653
Maybe after this bundle arrives,
we could go.

1313
01:57:05,889 --> 01:57:08,728
Sir.

1314
01:57:10,248 --> 01:57:16,565
We just got word.
Chaplin left for London on vacation.

1315
01:57:41,476 --> 01:57:42,636
Where's Mr. Chaplin?

1316
01:57:42,876 --> 01:57:45,155
We left him at the stern.

1317
01:57:45,395 --> 01:57:48,914
It's all right, darling.

1318
01:58:02,389 --> 01:58:07,347
What is it, sweetheart?

1319
01:58:07,867 --> 01:58:11,306
Is it Syd?

1320
01:58:11,985 --> 01:58:15,184
What is it?

1321
01:58:17,423 --> 01:58:21,182
They've thrown you out.

1322
01:58:21,422 --> 01:58:26,460
Thrown me out?
Thrown me out of what?

1323
01:58:27,620 --> 01:58:31,298
Of America.

1324
01:58:33,058 --> 01:58:36,936
I'm so sorry.

1325
01:58:39,895 --> 01:58:44,134
I can't go back.

1326
01:58:53,130 --> 01:58:57,609
There are nights when it's still hard
being in exile.

1327
01:58:57,849 --> 01:59:02,087
They surely wouldn't refuse you a
visa now. Thought of going back?

1328
01:59:02,327 --> 01:59:05,006
Let's go in.
- I have everything I need here.

1329
01:59:05,246 --> 01:59:07,165
It's cold.
- I like the cold.

1330
01:59:07,405 --> 01:59:08,525
I must go away.

1331
01:59:08,765 --> 01:59:09,604
I must go anyway.

1332
01:59:09,844 --> 01:59:13,243
The telephone!
- I heard it ringing, thank you.

1333
01:59:13,483 --> 01:59:19,081
No, George, in answer to your
question. I'm used to invitations.

1334
01:59:19,321 --> 01:59:21,840
It's been a long day.

1335
01:59:22,080 --> 01:59:24,519
You must be very tired.

1336
01:59:24,759 --> 01:59:27,438
Come on, George, finish it off.

1337
01:59:27,678 --> 01:59:29,917
The question mark.

1338
01:59:30,157 --> 01:59:32,236
What is it?

1339
01:59:32,476 --> 01:59:36,435
You mean that?

1340
01:59:37,954 --> 01:59:41,313
It was a personal matter.
Nothing relevant.

1341
01:59:41,553 --> 01:59:43,712
Tell me.

1342
01:59:43,952 --> 01:59:46,951
Okay.

1343
01:59:47,271 --> 01:59:49,350
The madness.

1344
01:59:49,590 --> 01:59:54,348
I wondered,
how much did it affect you?

1345
01:59:54,588 --> 01:59:57,307
What makes you think it did?

1346
01:59:57,547 --> 02:00:00,106
Your mother was certified insane,
and...

1347
02:00:00,346 --> 02:00:05,824
...your grandmother was as well,
and, uh...

1348
02:00:05,984 --> 02:00:11,742
That's not what dogged me, George.
It wasn't that.

1349
02:00:14,621 --> 02:00:16,500
It was...

1350
02:00:16,740 --> 02:00:21,618
...the knowledge that if you did what
I did, if you were a clown.

1351
02:00:21,858 --> 02:00:26,176
And you had passion to tell
a particular story...

1352
02:00:26,416 --> 02:00:30,495
...something...

1353
02:00:32,854 --> 02:00:35,413
...beyond.

1354
02:00:35,653 --> 02:00:37,852
You only had one chance
to get it right.

1355
02:00:38,092 --> 02:00:39,692
And I never did.

1356
02:00:39,931 --> 02:00:42,930
One never does. But you know that.

1357
02:00:43,170 --> 02:00:48,049
That's not the problem.

1358
02:00:51,967 --> 02:00:55,966
It's when you feel you're
getting close...

1359
02:00:56,206 --> 02:00:58,685
...but you can't make it.

1360
02:00:58,925 --> 02:01:02,923
You're not good enough.
You're not complete enough.

1361
02:01:03,163 --> 02:01:06,402
And despite all your fantasies...

1362
02:01:06,642 --> 02:01:09,001
...you're second-rate.

1363
02:01:09,241 --> 02:01:12,560
It's human.

1364
02:01:13,719 --> 02:01:17,758
And it's very hard.

1365
02:01:20,357 --> 02:01:21,956
Why not add that?

1366
02:01:22,196 --> 02:01:25,035
It's not important, really.

1367
02:01:25,275 --> 02:01:30,553
Ultimately, you're judged by what
you did, not what you didn't do.

1368
02:01:30,793 --> 02:01:34,752
And I didn't change things, I just...

1369
02:01:34,991 --> 02:01:38,550
...he just...

1370
02:01:38,710 --> 02:01:42,229
...cheered people up.

1371
02:01:42,469 --> 02:01:45,708
Not bad, that.

1372
02:02:28,572 --> 02:02:31,691
Charlie?

1373
02:02:35,409 --> 02:02:37,049
Charlie, dear.

1374
02:02:37,289 --> 02:02:40,808
I dreamed I was answering
questions for George. Silly.

1375
02:02:41,047 --> 02:02:46,046
California called again.
You have to give them an answer.

1376
02:02:46,286 --> 02:02:49,484
They took 20 years to decide,
I can take another afternoon.

1377
02:02:49,724 --> 02:02:53,603
Enough. Enough!

1378
02:03:07,558 --> 02:03:12,516
From Los Angeles, the 44th annual
Academy Awards Presentation.

1379
02:03:26,871 --> 02:03:29,270
Suppose they start throwing things.

1380
02:03:29,510 --> 02:03:31,029
Now that would be a story.

1381
02:03:31,269 --> 02:03:34,148
You never know... on the stage.

1382
02:03:34,388 --> 02:03:38,067
I can see the headlines:
"Amazing incident at Academy Awards".

1383
02:03:38,307 --> 02:03:42,985
"Chaplin Disappears under
Avalanche of Oscars".

1384
02:03:43,225 --> 02:03:45,984
Look, it's Walter.

1385
02:03:46,224 --> 02:03:48,103
Does that make you happy?

1386
02:03:48,343 --> 02:03:51,542
No.
- Crabby.

1387
02:03:51,782 --> 02:03:54,741
I shouldn't have let them show
film clips.

1388
02:03:54,981 --> 02:03:57,859
People will think they're old.

1389
02:03:58,099 --> 02:04:03,697
They are old.
Well over 50 years, some of them.

1390
02:04:03,857 --> 02:04:08,016
You know the worst thing
about age is...

1391
02:04:08,256 --> 02:04:11,694
...you can't defend yourself.

1392
02:04:11,934 --> 02:04:17,252
When I was young and handsome
and had my power...

1393
02:04:17,492 --> 02:04:19,572
...I'd make a movie...

1394
02:04:19,811 --> 02:04:24,410
...and make them laugh
and make them cry.

1395
02:04:24,650 --> 02:04:27,849
Now I'm at their mercy.

1396
02:04:28,088 --> 02:04:31,087
Come in.
- Go away.

1397
02:04:31,327 --> 02:04:35,806
We're ready for you, Mr. Chaplin.

1398
02:04:36,046 --> 02:04:38,125
Behave yourself.

1399
02:04:38,365 --> 02:04:41,883
Now the President of the Academy,
Mr. Daniel Taradash.

1400
02:04:42,123 --> 02:04:45,362
Remember the President
of the Academy, Daniel Taradash.

1401
02:04:45,602 --> 02:04:48,921
Taradash? Sounds like a spice.

1402
02:04:49,161 --> 02:04:52,400
The inscription reads:
"To Charles Chaplin...

1403
02:04:52,640 --> 02:04:55,958
...for the incalculable effect
he had making motion picture...

1404
02:04:56,198 --> 02:05:00,837
...the art form of this century. "

1405
02:05:01,076 --> 02:05:03,875
"Humour heightens our sense
of survival...

1406
02:05:04,115 --> 02:05:06,395
...and preserves our sanity. "

1407
02:05:06,634 --> 02:05:09,114
The words of Charlie Chaplin.

1408
02:05:09,353 --> 02:05:12,952
The abiding elements of Chaplin's
artistic conscience...

1409
02:05:13,192 --> 02:05:15,911
...as actor, writer, director, and...

1410
02:05:16,151 --> 02:05:19,830
...to quote W. C. Fields,
"greatest ballet dancer who ever lived".

1411
02:05:20,070 --> 02:05:22,509
A few years ago, Mr. Chaplin said:

1412
02:05:22,749 --> 02:05:26,067
"My only enemy is time. "

1413
02:05:26,307 --> 02:05:28,427
We respectfully disagree.

1414
02:05:28,666 --> 02:05:30,706
I'm leaving you here, darling.

1415
02:05:30,946 --> 02:05:37,183
My white dress... They mustn't
see anyone until the clips are over.

1416
02:05:37,623 --> 02:05:45,580
Time is Charlie Chaplin's dearest
and eternal friend.

1417
02:05:45,780 --> 02:05:47,779
Here is the proof.

1418
02:05:48,019 --> 02:05:53,937
Watch... remember... rejoice.

1419
02:10:51,069 --> 02:10:55,588
The End

1420
02:11:02,185 --> 02:11:05,904
Charles Spencer Chaplin accepted
his Special Academy Award.

1421
02:11:06,144 --> 02:11:10,782
Days later, he left Hollywood
and returned to Switzerland.

1422
02:11:11,022 --> 02:11:14,980
In 1975 Charlie
became sir Charles Chaplin...

1423
02:11:15,220 --> 02:11:20,099
...receiving his knighthood
from Queen Elizabeth in London.

1424
02:11:20,179 --> 02:11:24,377
During a 54-years career, Charlie
made 81 films. Five were talkies...

1425
02:11:24,617 --> 02:11:28,775
...67 where completed
before his 30th birthday.

1426
02:11:29,015 --> 02:11:32,814
Charlie died, aged 88,
on Christmas Day 1977 at his home...

1427
02:11:33,054 --> 02:11:36,933
...surrounded by Oona,
their children and grandchildren.

1428
02:11:37,172 --> 02:11:41,371
Hannah Chaplin, Charlie's mother,
spent the last 7 years of her life...

1429
02:11:41,611 --> 02:11:47,289
...in the house Charlie bought for her.

1430
02:11:48,048 --> 02:11:52,047
Sydney Chaplin retired to France
and spent summers at Charlie's home...

1431
02:11:52,287 --> 02:11:57,205
...in Switzerland.
He died on Charlie's 76th birthday.

1432
02:11:57,485 --> 02:12:01,044
Fred Karno, who gave Charlie
his first job, went bankrupt in 1926.

1433
02:12:01,284 --> 02:12:05,722
He died penniless 15 years later.

1434
02:12:05,922 --> 02:12:09,001
Hetty Kelly, Charlie's first love,
married a politician and died at 25.

1435
02:12:09,241 --> 02:12:14,679
She was the inspiration for many
of Charlie's screen heroines.

1436
02:12:14,919 --> 02:12:18,637
George Hayden
is a fictional character.

1437
02:12:18,877 --> 02:12:24,275
Charlie wrote "My Autobiography",
on which this film is partly based.

1438
02:12:24,795 --> 02:12:28,554
Mack Sennett's reign as the king
of comedy ended with the talkies.

1439
02:12:28,794 --> 02:12:33,952
He received a Special Oscar in 1937.

1440
02:12:34,552 --> 02:12:38,270
Mabel Normand was involved
in a drug and sex scandal...

1441
02:12:38,510 --> 02:12:41,909
...surrounding a murder in 1922.
She never acted again.

1442
02:12:42,149 --> 02:12:45,508
Edna Purviance was Charlie's leading
lady in more than 30 comedies.

1443
02:12:45,747 --> 02:12:51,425
Charlie kept her on the studio
payroll all her life.

1444
02:12:51,665 --> 02:12:56,064
Douglas Fairbanks founded United
Artists with Charlie, Mary and Griffith.

1445
02:12:56,304 --> 02:13:00,942
He died in his sleep
of a heart attack in 1939.

1446
02:13:01,182 --> 02:13:06,100
Mary Pickford competed with Charlie
as the highest earner in Hollywood.

1447
02:13:06,340 --> 02:13:11,498
"America's Sweetheart"
lived to be 86.

1448
02:13:11,938 --> 02:13:15,417
Mildred Harris was Charlie's first wife.

1449
02:13:15,657 --> 02:13:19,295
Her career faded
and she died an alcoholic at 43.

1450
02:13:19,535 --> 02:13:23,854
J. Edgar Hoover was FBI Director for
almost 50 years. Using sex secrets...

1451
02:13:24,094 --> 02:13:27,772
...illegally gathered by his agents
to manipulate powerful people.

1452
02:13:28,012 --> 02:13:33,250
Charlie's FBI file
was more than 1,900 pages.

1453
02:13:33,650 --> 02:13:37,129
Lita Grey was Charlie's second wife.

1454
02:13:37,369 --> 02:13:41,767
She and Sydney Jr. Were living
when this film was finished.

1455
02:13:42,007 --> 02:13:45,366
Paulette Goddard,
Charlie's third wife, retired in 1966.

1456
02:13:45,606 --> 02:13:52,483
She and her husband moved to
Switzerland, near Charlie and Oona.

1457
02:13:53,003 --> 02:13:56,922
Joan Barry spent most of her
remaining life in mental institutions.

1458
02:13:57,201 --> 02:14:02,160
Chaplin had to support Carol Ann
until she was 21.

1459
02:14:02,440 --> 02:14:06,358
Joseph Scott's courtroom speech is
based on contemporary accounts.

1460
02:14:06,598 --> 02:14:12,356
The paternity suit came to be regarded
as a major miscarriage of justice.

1461
02:14:12,596 --> 02:14:16,235
Oona O'Neill was 18 when she
married Charlie. They had 8 children.

1462
02:14:16,474 --> 02:14:20,753
When Charlie was barred from the
U.S., Oona renounced her citizenship.

1463
02:14:20,993 --> 02:14:27,750
